  "type": "Section",
  "number": "2.3",
  "title": "Velocity and Rates of Change",
  "body": " Velocity and Rates of Change   Recall that the initial interpretation of the derivative was as a \\textit{slope} of a tangent line. There is an alternate and arguable more useful interpretation of a derivative: as a \\textbf{rate of change}. First, we will consider possibly the most natural rate of change, which is velocity (the rate of change of position).  Calculus is often considered to be the mathematics of motion. Newton was a mathematician and physicist, and had a dynamic view of the world, and regarded functions as representing the amount of a quantity changing over time. Also, one initial motivation for the invention of calculus was Newton's study of the motion in physics, and of planets and other celestial bodies.    Motion and Velocity  Consider the motion of a moving object. For simplicity, consider an object that is moving along a straight line, which is said to be in rectilinear motion . In particular, the position of an object is given by . Then, the displacement is , the (signed) change in position. Recall that if the velocity of the object is constant, then this velocity is given by,   However, motion is often dynamic, i.e. not static, where the velocity of an object changes continuously over time. Then, velocity is not just a number, but a function of . In this case, things are more difficult. First, recall that we can still consider the average velocity of an object between times and , which is given by,   Using calculus, we can define the so-called instantaneous velocity of an object.  Broadly, the instantaneous velocity of an object (or simply its velocity ) is its velocity at a single specific point in time.  Instantaneous velocity is a subtle concept, since intuitively, any rate of change must involve two points to compare. If you only consider a snapshot in time, it doesn't seem to make sense to define a velocity at that single point. However, with the concepts of calculus, we can make this precise. Intuitively, instantaneous velocity is like the reading on a perfect speedometer. If the speedometer on a car says 50 km\/h this is interpreted as going 50 km\/h at that specific point in time, not as an average velocity over a time period. Of course, an actual speedometer measures velocity over a very small time interval, to give a very good approximation of the (theoretical) instantaneous velocity.  More precisely, let be the instantaneous velocity of an object at a time . Then, if is a small change in , then is approximately given by,   Then, we expect that this approximation improves as . Then, in the limit as , we intuitively expect the right hand side to be exactly equal to the instantaneous velocity at . Then, this the derivative of the position function ,   That is, if we make an infinitely small positive or negative number, and from both sides the difference quotient approaches the same value, then we define that that to be the instantaneous velocity at . In this way, instantaneous velocity at a time is the best constant approximation for the velocity around  .   Velocity is the derivative of position  For an object with position given (in 1 dimension) given by , its velocity is given by the derivative of . In other words,    Note that this models motion in 1 dimension, so the graph of the position function has its position on the vertical axis, and time on the horizontal axis. In this way, the object does not travel along the curve, but rather along the vertical axis.    Acceleration and Jerk  A similar analysis can be done with acceleration. If an object has velocity given by , then the average acceleration between times and is,   In a similar way, the instantaneous acceleration (or simply acceleration ) of an object is its acceleration at a single specific point in time. Let be the instantaneous velocity of an object at a time . Then, similarly, if is a small change in , then we expect that is approximately,   Then, similarly, as ,   Also, jerk is defined to be the rate of change of acceleration. If the jerk at time is denoted by , then,     Motion of a Projectile (Freefall Motion)  You may recall from high-school physics that an object in freefall motion (falling only under the force of gravity), has height given by,   where is the gravitational constant, is its initial velocity of the object (up or down), and is its initial height of the object. Then, the velocity function is,   This shows that the velocity of the object is a linear function (in ). Also, its acceleration is given by,   This shows that the acceleration of the object is constant, and is solely due to gravity.    More General Rates of Change  More generally, given a differentiable function , we can interpret the number as the rate of change of with respect to , as passes through the value . Or, the rate of change of at the point .  First, recall that for a function that is linear, for example, , the slope of this line is 2. We often also say that the rate of change in per change in is two units. This is because, for any increment in , the corresponding change in , , is given by,   In other words, . That is, for any change is , the corresponding change in is always twice that amount. Sometimes, we say that changes twice as fast as changes. We also say that 2 is the constant rate of change of with respect to . More generally, for a linear function,   We have, similarly,   so is the constant rate of change of with respect to . For a line, the relationship holds for all values of . Dividing by on both sides (if ),   More generally, if is a general function, the different quotient,   depends on and (i.e. is not constant). If its value is for some value of and , then the equation,   holds, and says that the total change in is exactly times the total change in over the interval . Then, we can say that over this interval changes on average times as fast as , and is the average rate of change of with respect to .   Let . The average rate of change of with respect to over the interval , is,    Then, the derivative is the limit as of this expression. Then,   Let . Then, the derivative, represents the instantaneous rate of change of with respect to at the point .   Again, the instantaneous rate of change of a quantity at a point can be thought of as the best numerical approximation of the rate of change of  around  .  Then, average velocity and instantaneous velocity are a special case of this, when represents distance (or displacement) and represents time.    Geometry: Area of a Circle  Recall that the area of a circle is a function of its radius , . Differentiating with respect to , we get,   Interestingly, this rate of change of area is exactly equal to the circumference of the circle. Also, for small ,   An intuitive way to see why this is true, is that when increases by , the added area forms a thin band around the existing circle. The area added by this thin band can be approximated by the area of a rectangle of width equal to the circumference of a circle, , and height equal to .  A similar analysis can be done for a sphere (intuitvely, the 3D analogue of a circle). Recall that the volume of a sphere of radius is given by,   Differentiating with respect to ,   Notice that this is precisely the formula for the surface area of a sphere.   "
