  "body": " The Chain Rule   Consider the function . Using only the power rule, we cannot differentiate , as the base of the power is not just but a function of , in particular . The chain rule gives insight for differentiating composite functions. The chain rule is among the most powerful rules for differentiation functions.  If is a function of , and is a function of , then is a function of . In particular, if and , then , a composite function. In the above example, we have , and . Then, . We want to consider the derivative of with respect to . That is, how fast does change when changes. In particular, how does this derivative relate to the derivatives and (which, in this example, are , and )?  Consider the general case. If and , and if is changing at a rate of with respect to , and is changing at a rate of with respect to , then is changing at a rate with respect to of their product, .    The Chain Rule  Let be functions, and consider their composition .   Let be functions, with so the composition is defined. Then, if is differentiable at , and is differentiable at the point , then the composite function is differentiable at , and,    Intuitively, the derivative of the composition is the product of the derivatives of and , with the caveat that the derivative of is evaluated at .  Using Leibniz notation, if and , then   where is evaluated at . This notation is particularly natural, because if and are treated as quotients, then could be cancelled from the numerator and denominator to get . However, recall that strictly speaking, is not the quotient of two quantities, but simply notation to represent the single quantity the derivative of with respect to .    Chain Rule for More Than Two Functions  The chain rule can be naturally extended to 3 functions, or an arbitrary number of functions.   Let be functions. If is differentiable at , is differentiable at the point , and is differentiable at , then is differentiable at , and,    Intuitively, start from the outside and make your way inside, like layers of an onion.    The derivative of of something is of that something, multiplied by the derivative of that something . Also, note that the chain rule is in some sense a generalization of other derivative rules, as for , then , and the chain rule becomes,   as expected.    Intuitive Proof of the Chain Rule  The chain rule is actually quite a subtle rule to prove, unlike some of the rules previously shown. First, we give an intuitive proof that works for almost all functions.   Proof using increments  With Leibniz notation, let . Then,   Then, the limit on the right is . Also, since is differentiable at , it is continuous, and so as , also. Thus,      Combining the Chain Rule with Other Differentiation Rules  The chain rule can be built-in to other differentiation formulas, so that they apply to arbitrary functions of rather than just . For example, recall the power rule for derivatives,   Then, for an arbitrary function ,    Generalized power rule  If is differentiable, then,    The generalized power rule can be proved using the limit definition of derivative, independent of the chain rule. This can be done for integers and rational powers using similar techniques used to prove those derivatives.   For example, the derivative of , using the chain rule, is . Using the limit definition of derivative, Using the limit product rule, as desired.    "
