  "id": "section-LEOF",
  "level": "1",
  "url": "section-LEOF.html",
  "type": "Section",
  "number": "4.2",
  "title": "Local Extrema of Functions",
  "body": " Local Extrema of Functions   A large application of calculus is for finding the maximums and minimums of functions.    Local\/Relative Extrema   Broadly, a relative maximum is a point such that for all near . Similarly, a relative minimum is a point such that for all near .   The singular of extrema is extremum (the word originates from Latin). An extremum refers to either a maximum or minimum.  Note that there some math textbooks have the convention that allows endpoints of the domain of a function to be possible local extrema. Whereas, other textbooks do not, requiring that a function be defined on both sides of its local extrema.    Critical Points  Let be a smooth function. Fermat recognized that maxima and minima corresponded with horizontal tangents, where the slope, or derivative, is equal to 0. Intuitively, a function can only have a local maximum if it is a point where the derivative exists and is equal to 0. More generally, the function can also have a sharp corner or cusp, where the derivative is not defined. Then, we call points like this critical points.   Let be defined at . Then, is a critical point of if either or does not exist ( is not differentiable at ).   This definition requires that be defined at its critical numbers, so that critical points correspond to points on the graph of . For example, does not have a critical number at .    Fermat's Theorem (Interior Extremum Theorem)   Fermat's theorem  Let be differentiable at . Then, if is a local extremum, then . Equivalently, if , then is not a local extremum of .   Fermat's theorem provides a necessary condition for determining local extrema. In other words, if we determine all of the points where , then this provides a list of candidate points for extrema to occur. Points where , or doesn't exist but does, are candidates for local extrema  In this way, determining possible extrema involves solving the equation . Note that the converse of Fermat's theorem is false, in that it is possible for , but does not have a local extremum at .  Consider at . Here, , which is equal to 0 only for . The function does have a horizontal tangent here, but it doesn't have a local extremum here.    First Derivative Test  Consider a differentiable function . From the graph of such functions, we can observe that a function cannot change from increasing to decreasing, without first going over a hill where the derivative is zero. Similarly, the graph of a function cannot change from decreasing to increasing without going through a valley . Together, we conclude that if the slope is never zero, then the graph can't change directions.   Let be continuous. If has no critical points on an interval , then is either always increasing on or always decreasing on .   More precisely, if the derivative is continuous, then by the intermediate value theorem, if it is positive at one point and negative at a different point, then it must be 0 somewhere between those two points. Then, if it is never 0, then it must be either always positive or always negative.  In this way, the critical points, and the points where the function is not defined, provide markings for intervals where the function can change from increasing to decreasing, or vise versa.   First derivative test  Let be a continuous function, be a critical point of . Then,  If changes from positive to negative at , then has a local maximum at .  If changes from negative to positive at , then has a local minimum at .  If is positive both to the left and right at , or is negative both to the left and right at , then has neither a local minimum nor a local maximum at .       Endpoints as Local Extrema (Advanced)  If we use the convention that endpoints can be local extrema, then we can also use insight from the derivative to determine if a function has a local max or local min at the endpoints of an interval.   For the function , it has a local minima at . However, the derivative . Notice that as , .   Let be a function, differentiable on . Then,    is a local maximum (minimum) if and only if,    is a local maximum (minimum) if and only if,      Remarks  Note that there is a difference between a maximum value and the point at which it is achieved. The maximum is the output of the function which is largest; the location of the maximum is the input of the function at which the maximum occurs. Sometimes, maximum point refers to the coordinate pair of the maximum. The terminology is somewhat mixed.  Technically, it is not true in general that functions which are differentiable have continuous derivatives. However, functions which fail to have continuous derivatives are quite pathological, and not relevant in any applications.    Advanced Examples   Prove that for , by showing that is increasing on .   In general, if satisfies , and on the interval , then on .    Fermat's Method of Adequality (Historical Note)  In 1629, Fermat developed a technique of finding extremum of functions, later published in his treatise Methodus ad disquirendam maximam et minimam (Method of Finding Maxima and Minima). This was before the development of the derivative.   Let .  Simplify the equation, and cancel like terms.  The remaining terms will contain a common factor of . Cancel out this common factor.  Discard terms which involve , i.e. set .  Solve for   Implicitly, this divided by , then sets , and has the similar paradox of the derivative. It is equivalent to the derivative method.   "
