  "id": "section-SGOF",
  "level": "1",
  "url": "section-SGOF.html",
  "type": "Section",
  "number": "4.6",
  "title": "Sketching Graphs of Functions",
  "body": " Sketching Graphs of Functions   Curve Sketching  Consider a function . The function itself, and its first and second derivative, provide useful information about the graph of . From pre-calculus, we can determine,   Points on the graph of , by evaluating .  The domain and range of .  The -intercepts and -intercepts.  Symmetry, if the function is even or odd.   Using calculus, we can determine additional properties of a graph.   Using limits, we can determine continuity (in particular, points of discontinuity), and any vertical or horizontal asymptotes.  From the first derivative , we can determine intervals of increase and decrease, and any local extrema.  From the second derivative , we can determine concavity and inflection points.   Notice the importance of algebra for solving the equations (to determine the -intercepts), (to determine the critical points), and (to determine the inflection points). In summary, calculus allows us to sketch graphs of functions more accurately.    Sketching the Graph of a Polynomial Function  First, we will consider sketching the graph of a polynomial function . The following steps provide a good outline as to how to sketch the graph of .   Intercepts . Determine any -intercepts and\/or the -intercept, by solving the polynomial equation , and by evaluating , respectively.  Symmetry . Determine any symmetry, i.e. if is an even or odd function.  Extrema and intervals of increase\/decrease . Determine , and determine any critical points by solving , and determine any local extrema using the first or second derivative test. Determine the intervals where is increasing and decreasing.  Concavity and inflection points . Determine , and determine any potential inflection points by solving . Determine the intervals where is concave up or down, and use this to determine the actual inflection points.  Plot the intercepts, critical points, and inflection points. Recall that critical points indicate horizontal tangents, and inflection points indicate changing concavity.  Polynomial end behavior . Consider the end behavior of , i.e. the behavior of as and .  Use all preceding information to determine the overall shape of the graph. If necessary, plot additional points.  Finally, connect the points with a smooth curve.     Quadratic Functions (Parabolas)  Consider a quadratic function . You might recall from pre-calculus that the vertex of this parabola is . This is made clear using calculus.  Determining critical points, , so . Using the first derivative test, this is a maximum or minimum, depending on the sign of .  Determining concavity, which is constant. If , then for all , and is concave up. If , then , and is concave down.    Cubic Polynomials  Note that a cubic function always has exactly one point of inflection, because the second derivative is a linear function, which has one root.  Note that a polynomial function of degree can have at most relative extrema, and at most inflection points.  If a polynomial has a double root, then it has a horizontal tangent there (like the function ).    Sketching the Graph of a Rational Function  The procedure for a rational function is somewhat similar to that of a polynomial function, except with rational functions we have a few extra characteristics.   Rational functions can have values of where does not exist (critical numbers), or where does not exist.  Rational functions have can have horizontal and vertical asymptotes, and may have holes.     Sketching Functions with Cusps and Vertical Tangents    Sketching a General Function    Sketching a Function Given Properties    "
