  "title": "Differentials, Local Linear Approximations",
  "body": " Differentials, Local Linear Approximations   Derivatives and Local Linearity  One fundamental property of functions which are differentiable is that they are locally linear . Roughly, this means that around a point where is differentiable, can be approximated by a linear function. Intuitively, this means that zooming in on the function result in the function looking as if it were linear. In particular, this linear function is the tangent line of at .    Approximating Small Changes  Recall that if is differentiable, then,   where is an increment in , and . Then, if is not taken in the limit to 0, but rather is a non-zero small number, then because is differentiable, the ratio will be approximately , or,   This reasoning was used in the opposite direction to define the derivative. That is, we take the ratio of and to approximate . On the other hand, if is known, then this approximation can be used in the other way to determine from and . Multiplying both sides by ,   In summary,   For a differentiable function and small ,      Differentials  Previously, we considered the expression as a single symbol representing the derivative. It is also helpful to interpret as the ratio of two very small real number quantities, called differentials .   Let . Then, a differential of x , , is given by , and is the differential of y , given by .     Local Linear Approximation  Using the approximation, if a point is known, we can approximate points near using the approximation,   If is differentiable at a point , then is locally linear around , that is, can be approximated with a line. In particular, it can be approximated with its tangent line,   This approximation works well for . The approximation is called a linearization.   Let be differentiable at . Then, the linearization (or linear approximation ) of at is the function,    This is useful because linear functions are very easy to evaluate, whereas a function may be difficult or more complicated to evaluate.  A linear approximation is just the tangent line of a function, but thought of as a function , rather than a line (say, ).  We most commonly consider approximations of functions at , in which case the tangent line formula is,    Sine  For , , and so . Then, the tangent line approximation is, Thus,     Cosine  For , , and so the tangent line approximation is,     Exponential  For , , and so the tangent line approximation is, Thus,     Logarithm  For the logarithmic function , it is not defined for . Instead, we can center the linear approximation . Then, for , , and so, Thus,     Binomial approximation  For the function (for some ), , and so, Thus, This is called the binomial approximation .     Remark About Differentials  Historically, differentials, and linear approximations, were quite useful for making approximations. However, in modern times, with computers, differentials have becomes less useful. Today, differentials are mostly a helpful conceptual idea.   "
